# Diving Master - Game Development Rules

## Project Context

- React Native game using Skia + Reanimated
- 2D underwater endless runner, 60fps target
- TypeScript strict mode enabled

## Architecture Patterns

### File Organization

src
/components # Skia visual components (Swimmer, Obstacles, etc.)
/hooks # Game logic hooks (useGameLoop, useCollision, etc.)
/types # TypeScript interfaces
/constants # Game balance values
/utils # Math helpers, collision detection

### Naming Conventions

- Components: PascalCase (e.g., `SeaTurtle.tsx`)
- Hooks: camelCase with `use` prefix (e.g., `useObstacles.ts`)
- Types: PascalCase with descriptive names (e.g., `ObstacleType`, `GameState`)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE in dedicated files

### Code Standards

- Use Skia primitives (Rect, Circle, Path, Image) for all rendering
- Reanimated shared values for animation state, React state for UI
- Always define TypeScript interfaces before implementation
- Prefer composition over inheritance for game entities

### Performance Rules

- NO setState in animation loops (use shared values)
- Object pooling for obstacles/collectibles
- Collision detection only for nearby entities
- Use useFrameCallback for game loop, never setInterval

### Import Order

1. React / React Native
2. Third-party (Skia, Reanimated)
3. Types
4. Constants
5. Hooks
6. Components
7. Utils
